We review the latest updates on:

1. VTS office tour activity, which was favorable: NYC tour volume in July 2025 was higher than the monthly average in 2024; and Trophy & Class A tour volume was up \(+20\%\) y/y in July. San Francisco tour volume in July 2025 was higher than the monthly average in 2024; and Trophy & Class A tour volume was up \(+9\%\) y/y in July.

2. July-August '25 QTD real-time office Costar leasing activity in Manhattan and San Francisco: NYC office leasing was down \(-26\%\) y/y in NYC and \(+14\%\) for San Francisco, where numbers could be revised higher as more data is collected.

3. Return to office trends by market from Placer.ai and Kastle: Seattle and NYC continue to improve while SF and LA remain stagnant per placer.ai data, while Kastle shows a decline in peak utilization in all major markets.
4. July '25 US office/CRE transaction volumes and office cap rates: The y/y trend for office transactions underperformed the overall market in June.
1. Office tour activity experienced a marginal drop in July '25, after a slight pick up in June.

- Nationwide: VTS Office Demand Index (VODI) is now tracking at \(71\%\) of 2018-2019 levels, down from \(74\%\) in June '25 and up from \(63\%\) in July '24. The Nationwide VTS index is based on 7 markets: Boston, Chicago, LA, NY, SF, DC; Seattle.- Recall, VODI reflects the total square footage of unique tenant requirements realized by touring activity in a given month relative to the total square footage. It is reported as an index (relative to the 2018-2019 average) to help interpretation and comparability across regions, and while not seasonally adjusted, is smoothed using a 3-month trailing average. The VODI indicates the pace at which office space may fill, but does not incorporate how it may empty due to low retention, or be impacted by

Regionally, the East Coast outperformed the Sunbelt and the West Coast (Exhibit 1) in July, where New York contributed to the strength: at \(99\%\) of pre- pandemic levels, outperforming all the other cities, followed by San Francisco at \(81\%\) in July '25 (Exhibit 2).

New York continues to see strong tour activity (Exhibit 3 compared to the pre- pandemic time period and versus San Francisco, but the spread to SF has narrowed recently. Compared to the monthly average total tour volume in 2023/2024 (Exhibit 4), July 2025 was higher in New York and in San Francisco. July 2025 was lower than the monthly average tour volume in each of 2023 and 2024 for Los Angeles, Houston, and Washington DC.

When considering only Trophy and Class A space: NYC July '25 tour volume tracked at \(- 3.3\mathrm{mn}\) SF, \(+20\%\) y/y (Exhibit 5), while San Francisco was \(1.5\mathrm{mn}\) SF, \(+9\%\) y/y. Additionally, the average tour size for NYC Trophy & Class A saw marginal sequential pick up, where July '25 tracked at \(2\mathrm{k}\) SF and June '25 tracked at \(21\mathrm{k}\) SF, vs an average of \(17\mathrm{k}\) SF/month in 2024 (Exhibit 6). Albeit at a smaller size, San Francisco also saw a slight pick up in average monthly tour size from \(16\mathrm{k}\) SF in 2024 to \(18\mathrm{k}\) SF in July 2025, while Atlanta and Austin saw a downward trend in July '25.

2. Office leasing in Manhattan and San Francisco: We also review office leasing data from CoStar (collected 8/27/25) in an effort to capture real-time activity in Manhattan and San Francisco; however, realize 3Q25 leasing numbers will be revised higher as data continues to be collected. Based on to-date data, we make the following comparisons on a y/y basis and compared to 2019:

New York leasing for July and August- to- date is \(21\%\) lower y/y (vs. the full months of July and August 2024), following \(+19\%\) y/y in FY24 (Exhibit 7). Compared to pre- pandemic corresponding 2019 levels, 3Q25 QTD Manhattan leasing is at \(70\%\) , from \(87\%\) in FY24 (Exhibit 8).

San Francisco/Bay Area leasing for July and August- to- date is \(+27\%\) y/y (vs. the full months of July and August 2024), following \(+23\%\) y/y in FY24. Exhibit 8 shows the shortfall versus 2019 maybe expanding: SF leasing activity in 2024/3Q25 QTD was about \(70\% /52\%\) of the corresponding 2019 amounts, but again: 3Q25 will be revised higher, and we will revisit it over time. Exhibit 10 shows that availability in San Francisco's FiDi and SOMA areas remains above \(25\%\) .
3. RTO: Overall Placer.ai data suggests nationwide office utilization is tracking at a higher level (close to \(70\%\) ) vs Kastle data (about \(50\%\) ) (Exhibit 11). More specifically:

According to Placer.ai, Seattle and NYC are seeing the most return to office (RTO), tracking at \(108\% /81\%\) of pre- pandemic levels currently, vs. \(90\% /82\%\) a year ago. San Francisco and Los Angeles remain lower, at \(57\% /62\%\) , but up from \(51\% /59\%\) last year (Exhibit 12).

- Kastle reports New York City is about \(51.1\%\) of pre-pandemic levels in August'25, vs \(31.1\%\) since the start of 2024, while San Francisco is about \(42.2\%\) of pre-pandemic levels, vs \(24.2\%\) since the start of 2024 (Exhibit 13).- According to Kastle reports: peak-day utilization recently declined in majority of markets (which could be expected for August), where Austin saw the steepest decline week over week (Exhibit 14).- Kastle also reports class A+ office building utilization is currently tracking at \(72.1\%\) of pre-pandemic levels vs \(52.3\%\) for properties overall (Exhibit 15).

- MSCI Real Assets shows US total CRE transaction volumes were \(+12.9\%\) in 2024 but was \(-7\%\) y/y in July '25 (Exhibit 16). We believe macro uncertainty could have caused the reversal in trend but note that MSCI's data collection is still ongoing, so we expect the final July '25 y/y results to be higher than currently shown.- To date, US office transaction volumes were \(+23.5\%\) in 2024 y/y and \(-16\%\) y/y for July'25 specifically (Exhibit 17).- For more details on CRE leasing and transactions, see CRE Services: JLL Estimate Update and Encouraging Early July Transaction Data (link, 8/12/25).

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global cover, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
